This paper is about developing a computational model for dialogue systems, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP) and computational linguistics (CL). Therefore, cs.CL is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of AI planning models, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (AI) and machine learning (ML), making cs.AI another likely sub-category. The development of a novel dialogue model and its implementation in a modular system involves the use of various techniques such as deep learning, reinforcement learning, and decision trees, which are all part of the sub-category of machine learning (ML) and specifically, deep learning (DL), making cs.LG another likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the curation and structuring of content, which falls under the category of information retrieval (IR), making cs.IR a likely sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the development of a novel ontological resource, which falls under the category of software development (SD), making cs.SD another likely sub-category.
